The roots at \( x = 1, 2, \ldots, 10 \) have multiplicities 1, 2,..., 10 respectively. 1. **Sign Changes at Each Root**: - Roots with odd multiplicity (1, 3, 5, 7, 9) cause the sign of \( P(x) \) to change. - Roots with even multiplicity (2, 4, 6, 8, 10) do not change the sign of \( P(x) \). 2. **Sign Analysis of Intervals**: - As \( x \to -\infty \), \( P(x) \) is negative. - Crossing \( x = 1 \) (odd multiplicity): Sign changes from negative to positive. - \( x = 2 \) (even multiplicity): Sign remains positive. - \( x = 3 \) (odd multiplicity): Sign changes from positive to negative. - \( x = 4 \) (even multiplicity): Sign remains negative. - \( x = 5 \) (odd multiplicity): Sign changes from negative to positive. - \( x = 6 \) (even multiplicity): Sign remains positive. - \( x = 7 \) (odd multiplicity): Sign changes from positive to negative. - \( x = 8 \) (even multiplicity): Sign remains negative. - \( x = 9 \) (odd multiplicity): Sign changes from negative to positive. - \( x = 10 \) (even multiplicity): Sign remains positive. - As \( x \to \infty \), \( P(x) \) is positive. 3. **Positive Intervals**: - The intervals where \( P(x) \) is positive are: \( (1, 2) \), \( (2, 3) \), \( (5, 6) \), \( (8, 9) \), \( (9, 10) \), and \( (10, \infty) \).
